  <static seed="1441" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/RationalEquations/solveRationalEquations3.pg">
    <statement><p>Solve the equation.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ {\frac{r-3}{5r+9}} = \frac{3}{7} }</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="34" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left\{-6\right\}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To get rid of all fractions in this equation, we multiple all terms with the common denominator. In this equation, the common denominator is <m>{7\mathopen{}\left(5r+9\right)}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   {\frac{r-3}{5r+9}} \amp = \frac{3}{7} \\
   {\frac{r-3}{5r+9}} \cdot {7\mathopen{}\left(5r+9\right)} \amp = \frac{3}{7} \cdot {7\mathopen{}\left(5r+9\right)} \\
   7(r - 3) \amp = 3(5r+9) \\
   7r - 21 \amp = 15r+27 \\
   7r - 21  \mathbf{-15r + 21} \amp = 15r+27 \mathbf{-15r + 21}  \\
   -8r \amp = 48 \\
   \frac{-8r}{-8} \amp = \frac{48}{-8} \\
   r \amp = -6
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>We must check solutions when we solve rational equations. By the original equation, the domain condition is <m>{7\mathopen{}\left(5r+9\right)} \ne 0</m>, or <m>r \ne -\frac{9}{5}</m>. This doesn<rsq/>t conflict with the solution above, so the solution is <m>r = -6</m>.</p>
</solution>
